@node Buffer protection and alerts
@section Buffer protection and alerts

@vindex ai-extras-protect-buffers
The user option @code{ai-extras-protect-buffers} controls whether killing an AI session buffer requires confirmation.  When set to non-@code{nil} (the default), attempting to kill a buffer with a live session process triggers a yes-or-no prompt.  Buffers whose process has already exited (e.g., via the @samp{/exit} command) are killed without prompting.  Set this to @code{nil} if you prefer to close sessions without confirmation.

@vindex ai-extras-alert-on-ready
The user option @code{ai-extras-alert-on-ready} enables OS notifications when an AI session finishes responding and is waiting for input.  The default is @code{nil}.  Toggle it interactively with @code{ai-extras-toggle-alert} (@ref{Alert commands}).

@vindex ai-extras-alert-style
The user option @code{ai-extras-alert-style} determines the form of the notification.  Accepted values are @code{visual} (an OS notification via the @samp{alert} package), @code{sound} (an audio alert), or @code{both} (the default).  This option only takes effect when @code{ai-extras-alert-on-ready} is non-@code{nil}.

@vindex ai-extras-alert-sound
The user option @code{ai-extras-alert-sound} specifies the path to the sound file played for audio alerts.  The default is @samp{/System/Library/Sounds/Glass.aiff}, a macOS system sound.  Change this to any audio file playable by @samp{afplay}.

@node Terminal rendering
@section Terminal rendering

@vindex ai-extras-sigwinch-delay
The user option @code{ai-extras-sigwinch-delay} controls the delay in seconds before sending a @samp{SIGWINCH} signal to fix terminal rendering after session startup.  The default is @samp{0.5} seconds.  AI CLI tools running in the @samp{eat} terminal emulator sometimes render incorrectly due to a race condition in terminal size negotiation.  Sending @samp{SIGWINCH} forces the TUI to re-query dimensions and redraw.  Increase this value if the fix does not take effect on slower systems.

