@node Session management
@section Session management

@findex ai-extras-start-or-switch
The command @code{ai-extras-start-or-switch} is the primary entry point for working with AI sessions.  When no sessions are active across any registered backend, it starts a new session.  If only one backend is registered, it starts that backend directly.  If multiple backends are available, it prompts the user to choose one.

When sessions already exist, the command opens a transient menu.  The first column lists two actions: @samp{w} to jump to the most recently waiting session, and @samp{e} to start a new session.  The remaining columns display active sessions grouped by account.  When a backend provides an @code{:account} function, its sessions are grouped under a heading named after the account.  Sessions from backends without an @code{:account} function appear at the top of the list without a group heading, since these backends do not support multi-account grouping.  Within each group, sessions are sorted by their assigned key.  Pressing a key instantly switches to that session.  The first eight sessions are bound to home-row keys (@samp{a}, @samp{s}, @samp{d}, @samp{f}, @samp{j}, @samp{k}, @samp{l}, @samp{;}); additional sessions fall back to other letter keys (@samp{g}, @samp{h}, then upper- and lower-row letters, excluding @samp{w} and @samp{e} which are reserved for actions).  Sessions waiting for user input are highlighted with the @code{ai-extras-waiting} face (inherits @code{success} by default, signalling ``ready for input''), or with @code{ai-extras-waiting-with-background} (inherits @code{warning} by default) when the backend's @code{:has-background-tasks-p} function reports that the session has ongoing background work (for example, running background Bash processes or Task agents).  The warning-coloured highlight draws attention to sessions that are idle but still busy under the hood.

@findex ai-extras-jump-to-waiting
The command @code{ai-extras-jump-to-waiting} switches to the AI session that most recently started waiting for user input.  This is useful when running multiple sessions in parallel and you want to attend to whichever one finished first.  If no sessions are waiting, it displays a message.

@node Alert commands
@section Alert commands

@findex ai-extras-toggle-alert
The command @code{ai-extras-toggle-alert} toggles the value of @code{ai-extras-alert-on-ready} and reports the new state.  This provides a quick way to enable or disable notifications without visiting the customization interface.

@node Terminal commands
@section Terminal commands

@findex ai-extras-fix-rendering
The command @code{ai-extras-fix-rendering} sends a @samp{SIGWINCH} signal to the current buffer's process after a short delay controlled by @code{ai-extras-sigwinch-delay} (@ref{Terminal rendering}).  Use this when the terminal display is garbled after startup or after resizing the window.

@findex ai-extras-disable-scrollback-truncation
The command @code{ai-extras-disable-scrollback-truncation} removes @samp{eat}'s default scrollback size limit for the current buffer.  Without this, the @samp{eat} terminal emulator truncates output to @code{eat-term-scrollback-size} lines, causing older session output to disappear.  This is called automatically on session startup.

@findex ai-extras-snippet-tab
The command @code{ai-extras-snippet-tab} attempts to expand a yasnippet key at the terminal prompt.  If no snippet key matches, it sends a literal @samp{TAB} character to the terminal.  This command is bound to @samp{TAB} in AI session buffers when yasnippet is available.

@node Dispatched tool commands
@section Dispatched tool commands

@findex ai-extras-run-skill
The command @code{ai-extras-run-skill} discovers skills from all registered backends and presents them in a single completion list.  Each candidate is annotated with the backend it belongs to (e.g., @samp{[Claude Code]} or @samp{[Codex]}), so the user can see at a glance which tool will execute the skill.  After selecting a skill, the command prompts for arguments when the skill declares an argument hint, argument source, or argument choices in its frontmatter.  It then dispatches execution to the appropriate backend's @code{:run-skill} handler.

This unified approach eliminates the need to choose a backend before browsing skills.  Backends that provide a @code{:discover-skills} function in their registration plist contribute their skills to the aggregated list (@ref{Backend registration}).

@findex ai-extras-handoff
@findex ai-extras-audit-project
@findex ai-extras-debug-backtrace
@findex ai-extras-exit
@findex ai-extras-restart
The remaining dispatched commands (@code{ai-extras-handoff}, @code{ai-extras-audit-project}, @code{ai-extras-debug-backtrace}, @code{ai-extras-exit}, @code{ai-extras-restart}) resolve a single backend from the current buffer context or by prompting, then delegate to that backend's handler.

