@node Backend registration
@section Backend registration

@findex ai-extras-register-backend
The function @code{ai-extras-register-backend} registers an AI tool as a backend.  It takes a symbol (e.g., @code{claude-code} or @code{codex}) and a property list with keys describing how to interact with that tool's sessions.  Required keys include @code{:buffer-p} (a predicate), @code{:find-all-buffers}, @code{:send-command}, @code{:start-new}, and @code{:icon}.

Optional keys include @code{:account}, a function that takes a buffer and returns the account name as a string or nil.  When provided, the session switcher groups sessions by account, creating a labeled section per account (@ref{Session management}).  Backends that omit @code{:account} have their sessions listed without a group heading.  Another optional key is @code{:has-background-tasks-p}, a predicate that takes a buffer and returns non-nil when the session has ongoing background work (e.g. background Bash processes or Task agents) even though it is idle for input.  When the backend reports that a waiting session has background work, the switcher highlights it with the @code{ai-extras-waiting-with-background} face instead of @code{ai-extras-waiting} (@ref{Session management}).  Other optional keys include @code{:discover-skills}, a function returning a list of skill plists, and @code{:run-skill}, a function that accepts a skill name and optional arguments.  When a backend provides @code{:discover-skills}, its skills appear in the aggregated list shown by @code{ai-extras-run-skill} (@ref{Dispatched tool commands}).

Backend registration is typically done at load time by extension packages like @samp{claude-code-extras.el} and @samp{codex-extras.el}.

@node SVG icons
@section SVG icons

@findex ai-extras-svg-icon
The function @code{ai-extras-svg-icon} renders an SVG string as an inline image suitable for the mode line, tab bar, or transient menus.  It replaces occurrences of @samp{currentColor} in the SVG data with the foreground color of FACE (defaulting to @code{default}), then creates an image scaled to match the font height of that face.  The result is a propertized string with a @code{display} image property.  Callers that display the icon in the mode line should pass @code{mode-line} as FACE so the color matches the mode-line foreground.

Backends use this function in their @code{:icon} lambda to display official product logos (e.g., the Clawd pixel-art mascot or the OpenAI knot) instead of generic icon-font glyphs.  The @code{:icon} function accepts an optional FACE argument and forwards it to @code{ai-extras-svg-icon}.  When Emacs lacks SVG support (no @samp{librsvg}), the function returns an empty string, and backends fall back to short text abbreviations.

@node Display names
@section Display names

@findex ai-extras-display-name
The function @code{ai-extras-display-name} returns a human-readable name for a session buffer.  When the project name is unique among active sessions, it returns just the project name (e.g., @samp{my-project}).  When multiple sessions share the same project, it disambiguates with the instance name (e.g., @samp{my-project:branch-abc}).  Results are cached and refreshed automatically when sessions are created or destroyed.

@node Notification display
@section Notification display

@findex ai-extras-notify
The function @code{ai-extras-notify} displays a notification with a title and message.  It always shows a minibuffer message.  When @code{ai-extras-alert-on-ready} is enabled, it additionally fires visual and/or audio alerts according to @code{ai-extras-alert-style} (@ref{Buffer protection and alerts}).

@findex ai-extras-alert-indicator
The function @code{ai-extras-alert-indicator} returns a bell emoji reflecting the current alert state, suitable for use in modeline segments.

@node Buffer protection
@section Buffer protection

@findex ai-extras-protect-buffer
The function @code{ai-extras-protect-buffer} is intended for use in @code{kill-buffer-query-functions}.  It returns @code{t} (allow kill) when @code{ai-extras-protect-buffers} is @code{nil}, the buffer is not an AI session, or the session process has exited.  Otherwise it prompts for confirmation.

@findex ai-extras-kill-session-buffer
The command @code{ai-extras-kill-session-buffer} terminates the CLI process in the current buffer and kills the buffer, bypassing confirmation.  It signals an error unless the current buffer is an AI session.

@node Transient menu
@chapter Transient menu

@findex ai-extras-menu
The command @code{ai-extras-menu} opens a unified transient dispatch menu for all AI session commands.  The base menu is a single column group with three columns.  The left column stacks Sessions and Buffer, the middle column stacks Tools and Alerts, and the right column contains Options.  Using a single group ensures all columns are vertically aligned.

Shared tool commands dispatch to the appropriate backend.  @code{ai-extras-run-skill} aggregates skills from all backends into a single list (@ref{Dispatched tool commands}).  The remaining dispatched commands (@code{ai-extras-handoff}, @code{ai-extras-audit-project}, @code{ai-extras-debug-backtrace}) resolve a backend from the current buffer context; when not in a session buffer and multiple backends are registered, the user is prompted to choose one.  The backend prompt displays each backend's SVG icon to the left of its label (@ref{SVG icons}).

Backend-specific extension packages append their own entries to the menu at load time via @code{transient-append-suffix}.  For example, @samp{claude-code-extras.el} adds account selection, branch navigation, batch processing, and status polling entries, while @samp{codex-extras.el} adds a Codex theme sync toggle.

